WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:06.080 --> 00:00:08.029
SPEAKER 1: Thank you
all for being here.

00:00:08.029 --> 00:00:10.150
And let's begin.

00:00:10.150 --> 00:00:13.970
So first off, Judith, we
just want to start with that,

00:00:13.970 --> 00:00:16.520
beginning with, what
exactly is an empath,

00:00:16.520 --> 00:00:18.440
if you could speak upon that?

00:00:18.440 --> 00:00:19.940
JUDITH ORLOFF: So
I just want to say

00:00:19.940 --> 00:00:21.490
how excited I am to be here.

00:00:21.490 --> 00:00:23.590
The energy here
is so incredible.

00:00:23.590 --> 00:00:25.880
It's so beautiful.

00:00:25.880 --> 00:00:28.010
As an empath, I'm
an emotional sponge,

00:00:28.010 --> 00:00:31.550
and I tend to absorb other
people's emotions, or even

00:00:31.550 --> 00:00:35.030
physical symptoms, or the energy
of a place into my own body.

00:00:35.030 --> 00:00:39.170
But when it's like this,
it's a true pleasure.

00:00:39.170 --> 00:00:41.130
It's a beautiful
work environment.

00:00:41.130 --> 00:00:43.560
So I'm very grateful to be here.

00:00:43.560 --> 00:00:47.270
I'm a psychiatrist in Santa
Monica, and I'm also an empath.

00:00:47.270 --> 00:00:50.300
And so I combine traditional
psychiatric skills

00:00:50.300 --> 00:00:54.560
with my ability to intuit what's
going on in the environment.

00:00:54.560 --> 00:00:57.170
And being an
empath, somebody who

00:00:57.170 --> 00:01:00.920
is very sensitive, very
intuitive, very open,

00:01:00.920 --> 00:01:03.390
but they tend to take on
the stress of the world

00:01:03.390 --> 00:01:07.200
because they don't have the same
filters that other people have.

00:01:07.200 --> 00:01:11.750
And so I feel everything,
which can be a plus and minus.

00:01:11.750 --> 00:01:14.300
And so I wanted to write
the "Empath Survival

00:01:14.300 --> 00:01:16.160
Guide," to give
people skills how

00:01:16.160 --> 00:01:19.250
not to absorb the stress
of others, particularly

00:01:19.250 --> 00:01:20.510
in the work environment.

00:01:20.510 --> 00:01:22.280
If you're next to
people, perhaps you're

00:01:22.280 --> 00:01:25.650
uncomfortable with, how to
just hold a space for them,

00:01:25.650 --> 00:01:27.200
but not take it on.

00:01:27.200 --> 00:01:28.940
Because empaths take it on.

00:01:28.940 --> 00:01:31.830
And as a result, I
can get exhausted,

00:01:31.830 --> 00:01:33.290
or when I was a
child, I couldn't

00:01:33.290 --> 00:01:35.660
go into shopping malls
or crowded places

00:01:35.660 --> 00:01:38.690
because I'd go in fine
and then I'd walk out

00:01:38.690 --> 00:01:42.410
with an ache, or pain,
or anxiety, or exhaustion

00:01:42.410 --> 00:01:43.860
that I didn't have before.

00:01:43.860 --> 00:01:47.690
And I didn't realize then, as a
little girl, that I was picking

00:01:47.690 --> 00:01:52.700
up the energy and the
emotions of other people,

00:01:52.700 --> 00:01:55.430
that the whole phenomena
of emotional contagion that

00:01:55.430 --> 00:01:58.980
can happen that we know so
much now that-- for instance,

00:01:58.980 --> 00:02:01.340
if you're in a
children's ward, a baby

00:02:01.340 --> 00:02:03.500
ward in the hospital, if
one baby starts crying,

00:02:03.500 --> 00:02:05.510
the rest of them start crying.

00:02:05.510 --> 00:02:07.550
Or if you're in a
work environment

00:02:07.550 --> 00:02:11.780
and somebody has very negative
energy and is a downer,

00:02:11.780 --> 00:02:15.080
it can spread to the rest
of the people like a virus.

00:02:15.080 --> 00:02:18.560
And so as an empath, that's
particularly intense.

00:02:18.560 --> 00:02:21.290
And so I want to say
that this is a gift,

00:02:21.290 --> 00:02:24.110
and we need to learn how
to manage it as well.

00:02:28.580 --> 00:02:31.150
SPEAKER 2: So I
think you answered

00:02:31.150 --> 00:02:33.580
part of my second question,
or the second question

00:02:33.580 --> 00:02:37.720
that we've put together, but
it was, how did you become

00:02:37.720 --> 00:02:40.540
involved in studying empathy?

00:02:40.540 --> 00:02:44.680
And then, because
this group is very

00:02:44.680 --> 00:02:47.380
curious and
science-minded, I wondered

00:02:47.380 --> 00:02:50.260
if you could speak
about the science that

00:02:50.260 --> 00:02:52.680
has come out about empathy.

00:02:52.680 --> 00:02:57.440
JUDITH ORLOFF: The science
behind empathy is fascinating.

00:02:57.440 --> 00:03:00.220
It is believed that there's
a spectrum of empathy.

00:03:00.220 --> 00:03:02.590
Whereas ordinary empathy,
which is so beautiful--

00:03:02.590 --> 00:03:04.930
it's where you can feel
something for someone else

00:03:04.930 --> 00:03:07.480
as they're going through
it, but you don't actually

00:03:07.480 --> 00:03:09.590
take it on in your own body.

00:03:09.590 --> 00:03:13.510
So up higher on the spectrum
are the highly sensitive people

00:03:13.510 --> 00:03:17.640
who have sensitivity to light,
sound, noise, like to be alone,

00:03:17.640 --> 00:03:21.040
like to be in nature,
replenish themselves

00:03:21.040 --> 00:03:23.820
by themselves rather
than in crowds of people

00:03:23.820 --> 00:03:25.120
or going to parties.

00:03:25.120 --> 00:03:27.730
And then on the high
end, is the empath

00:03:27.730 --> 00:03:30.760
who absorbs energy
from other people

00:03:30.760 --> 00:03:32.890
and is extremely empathic.

00:03:32.890 --> 00:03:36.370
And the science behind
it includes mirror neuron

00:03:36.370 --> 00:03:38.800
research, where it's
thought that with people

00:03:38.800 --> 00:03:42.400
with extreme empathy-- the
mirror neurons, the compassion

00:03:42.400 --> 00:03:44.870
neurons of the brain,
are hyperactive.

00:03:44.870 --> 00:03:46.890
Where they're just
working overtime,

00:03:46.890 --> 00:03:49.300
where we feel compassion
for everything,

00:03:49.300 --> 00:03:51.270
and everybody, and the world.

00:03:51.270 --> 00:03:53.080
And it could get to be too much.

00:03:53.080 --> 00:03:56.050
But it's thought that the
mirror neurons are really

00:03:56.050 --> 00:04:01.690
working overtime as compared to
a narcissist or a sociopath who

00:04:01.690 --> 00:04:04.180
have empathy deficient
disorder, meaning

00:04:04.180 --> 00:04:06.770
they don't really have
empathy as we know it.

00:04:06.770 --> 00:04:10.330
Their mirror neurons are
thought to be hypoactive,

00:04:10.330 --> 00:04:13.810
meaning they're not really
functioning at full tilt.

00:04:13.810 --> 00:04:15.490
And then there's
the whole phenomena

00:04:15.490 --> 00:04:18.070
of emotional contagion,
which I mentioned.

00:04:18.070 --> 00:04:20.740
It's that emotions
can be catchy,

00:04:20.740 --> 00:04:23.800
and we are sensitive to
how people are around us.

00:04:23.800 --> 00:04:27.970
Their emotions affect us,
even if we're not empaths.

00:04:27.970 --> 00:04:30.490
Somebody else's emotions,
if they come into your work

00:04:30.490 --> 00:04:33.130
environment and
they're a drama queen,

00:04:33.130 --> 00:04:36.070
or they're a chronic
talker, or they're

00:04:36.070 --> 00:04:38.530
a victim where they
always want to talk

00:04:38.530 --> 00:04:40.720
about themselves and
their victim status,

00:04:40.720 --> 00:04:42.580
it brings you down.

00:04:42.580 --> 00:04:45.550
If you're an open-hearted
person, if you're open

00:04:45.550 --> 00:04:47.980
and you feel all this,
your energy goes down.

00:04:47.980 --> 00:04:51.250
So it's important to
understand emotional contagion.

00:04:51.250 --> 00:04:54.550
And also, the concept of
dopamine, where dopamine

00:04:54.550 --> 00:04:56.230
is a pleasure hormone.

00:04:56.230 --> 00:04:58.180
And it's thought
that empaths need

00:04:58.180 --> 00:05:01.390
a smaller amount of
dopamine to feel good

00:05:01.390 --> 00:05:05.380
than extroverts who get their
dopamine fix from going out

00:05:05.380 --> 00:05:09.020
with big parties, and big
events, and football games.

00:05:09.020 --> 00:05:12.840
You get a large
dopamine hit with that.

00:05:12.840 --> 00:05:16.660
But empaths get satisfied
by very little interaction.

00:05:16.660 --> 00:05:20.770
For instance, as an empath, I
love one-to-one interactions.

00:05:20.770 --> 00:05:22.160
I really enjoy them.

00:05:22.160 --> 00:05:23.860
But when it gets to
be a lot of people,

00:05:23.860 --> 00:05:25.930
it gets overwhelming for me.

00:05:25.930 --> 00:05:27.450
I love to connect.

00:05:27.450 --> 00:05:30.790
And too many people, on a
personal level, is hard for me.

00:05:30.790 --> 00:05:33.430
I speak to large groups,
and that's a bit different.

00:05:33.430 --> 00:05:35.170
But on a personal
level, I prefer

00:05:35.170 --> 00:05:37.000
to have small gatherings.

00:05:37.000 --> 00:05:41.410
And it could be the dopamine
explanation in research,

00:05:41.410 --> 00:05:43.810
because I require very little.

00:05:43.810 --> 00:05:46.990
I get filled very
easily by happiness.

00:05:46.990 --> 00:05:50.650
And I get drained if I stay in
a social situation for too long.

00:05:50.650 --> 00:05:54.100
It's too much for me because
I get overstimulated.

00:05:54.100 --> 00:05:57.710
And too much is coming in too
fast with sensory overload.

00:05:57.710 --> 00:06:00.670
So if you're an empath or
you're a sensitive person,

00:06:00.670 --> 00:06:04.100
it's good to look at
the science behind it.

00:06:04.100 --> 00:06:06.790
It's thought, also, the
electromagnetic energy

00:06:06.790 --> 00:06:10.760
from the heart and the
brain gives off information.

00:06:10.760 --> 00:06:13.000
And so we're
transmitting information.

00:06:13.000 --> 00:06:15.880
And if you're sensitive,
you're an empath,

00:06:15.880 --> 00:06:17.170
you can feel all of this.

00:06:17.170 --> 00:06:18.850
But the problem
is, empaths don't

00:06:18.850 --> 00:06:20.300
know how to manage all this.

00:06:20.300 --> 00:06:22.600
And I think if you
break down the science

00:06:22.600 --> 00:06:26.740
and you begin to look at the
various aspects of the science,

00:06:26.740 --> 00:06:30.880
it's very useful in terms of
explaining what you're feeling

00:06:30.880 --> 00:06:34.210
and why you're feeling it.

00:06:34.210 --> 00:06:36.130
