SPEAKER 1: So I brought
an instructor weekly,

00:37:11.600 --> 00:37:16.280
and you can join us at the
LAX Tai chi group in emails.

00:37:16.280 --> 00:37:20.900
And it's Mondays
from 4:30 to 5:30.

00:37:20.900 --> 00:37:23.390
There is a cost because I've
brought in the instructor,

00:37:23.390 --> 00:37:25.520
but we meet over in
the Bin 5 courtyard,

00:37:25.520 --> 00:37:28.730
or inside the bunker
when it's cold.

00:37:28.730 --> 00:37:31.580
JUDITH ORLOFF: That's fantastic.

00:37:31.580 --> 00:37:36.150
AUDIENCE: A lot of people
who are not empathic--

00:37:36.150 --> 00:37:39.150
they might be kind, they
might be changing the world,

00:37:39.150 --> 00:37:42.900
they might not be
necessarily narcissistic.

00:37:42.900 --> 00:37:47.640
Is there some tool, some
kind of Myers-Briggs

00:37:47.640 --> 00:37:51.000
personality test so
that they recognize

00:37:51.000 --> 00:37:53.569
that they're not empathic?

00:37:53.569 --> 00:37:54.360
JUDITH ORLOFF: Yes.

00:37:54.360 --> 00:37:58.170
AUDIENCE: And if there is one,
then what do we do with it?

00:37:58.170 --> 00:38:02.100
What's we know that a
person is not empathic, what

00:38:02.100 --> 00:38:04.770
other actions, apart
from meditation,

00:38:04.770 --> 00:38:09.180
can a person take
to develop that?

00:38:09.180 --> 00:38:11.550
JUDITH ORLOFF: That's
a great question.

00:38:11.550 --> 00:38:14.430
How do you identify it
somebody doesn't have empathy?

00:38:14.430 --> 00:38:16.210
And then how do
you deal with it?

00:38:16.210 --> 00:38:17.760
OK.

00:38:17.760 --> 00:38:20.640
The best way is to
provoke a small conflict.

00:38:20.640 --> 00:38:23.110
Because if you
provoke a conflict,

00:38:23.110 --> 00:38:25.300
you can see how
they deal with it.

00:38:25.300 --> 00:38:29.686
If they have-- why
are you laughing?

00:38:29.686 --> 00:38:30.810
SPEAKER 2: I hate conflict.

00:38:30.810 --> 00:38:32.250
JUDITH ORLOFF:
You hate conflict.

00:38:32.250 --> 00:38:33.962
SPEAKER 2: So now I'm
going to creed that that

00:38:33.962 --> 00:38:35.180
would be really hard for me.

00:38:35.180 --> 00:38:37.950
JUDITH ORLOFF: Well,
a little conflict.

00:38:37.950 --> 00:38:40.481
They say, let's
meet today at 10:00.

00:38:40.481 --> 00:38:42.230
And you say, well, I
can't do it at 10:00,

00:38:42.230 --> 00:38:43.560
but I'll do it at 11:00.

00:38:43.560 --> 00:38:46.350
Even just a little
thing like that,

00:38:46.350 --> 00:38:48.210
somebody who
doesn't have empathy

00:38:48.210 --> 00:38:51.000
is going to become cold,
withholding, judgmental,

00:38:51.000 --> 00:38:54.660
punishing, and change
their very nice personality

00:38:54.660 --> 00:38:56.340
into a different one.

00:38:56.340 --> 00:39:00.270
And so narcissists
who don't have empathy

00:39:00.270 --> 00:39:04.110
don't like it when you
don't do things their way.

00:39:04.110 --> 00:39:05.430
Have you met people like that?

00:39:05.430 --> 00:39:08.310
AUDIENCE: No, I just meant
to say that maybe there's

00:39:08.310 --> 00:39:10.830
another classification out
there, which is basically

00:39:10.830 --> 00:39:12.505
kind people, not narcissists.

00:39:12.505 --> 00:39:13.630
JUDITH ORLOFF: Kind people.

00:39:13.630 --> 00:39:15.660
AUDIENCE: But they
are not empathic.

00:39:15.660 --> 00:39:19.290
They don't have
that mirror neurons.

00:39:19.290 --> 00:39:21.960
They do not understand
what are you going through,

00:39:21.960 --> 00:39:25.380
so they cannot relate
to you in general.

00:39:25.380 --> 00:39:27.520
They are sympathetic,
but not empathic.

00:39:27.520 --> 00:39:29.520
JUDITH ORLOFF: They're
very kind people, though.

00:39:29.520 --> 00:39:30.270
Not narcissists.

00:39:30.270 --> 00:39:31.559
AUDIENCE: But they are not--

00:39:31.559 --> 00:39:33.600
they cannot understand
what you're going through,

00:39:33.600 --> 00:39:36.090
your emotional state.

00:39:36.090 --> 00:39:39.450
Let's say you come in,
and you look very sad.

00:39:39.450 --> 00:39:40.730
And you don't want to work.

00:39:40.730 --> 00:39:42.480
Let's say it's a manager
or somebody else.

00:39:42.480 --> 00:39:44.240
But he doesn't recognize that.

00:39:44.240 --> 00:39:46.990
And you're thinking, why
does he not recognize that?

00:39:46.990 --> 00:39:48.690
So they lack empathy.

00:39:48.690 --> 00:39:52.549
They don't know that they're
trampling over somebody.

00:39:52.549 --> 00:39:53.340
JUDITH ORLOFF: Yes.

00:39:53.340 --> 00:39:56.340
Let me make the distinction of
lacking empathy versus someone

00:39:56.340 --> 00:39:58.050
just being in their heads.

00:39:58.050 --> 00:40:00.174
Because sometimes,
people are self-absorbed

00:40:00.174 --> 00:40:01.590
or in their heads,
and they're not

00:40:01.590 --> 00:40:03.274
tuning in emotionally to you.

00:40:03.274 --> 00:40:04.690
AUDIENCE: And
that's what happens.

00:40:04.690 --> 00:40:06.150
JUDITH ORLOFF: But that
doesn't necessarily

00:40:06.150 --> 00:40:07.390
make them a narcissist.

00:40:07.390 --> 00:40:09.360
And they could be
the kindest person,

00:40:09.360 --> 00:40:12.130
but they can also be out of
touch with their feelings.

00:40:12.130 --> 00:40:14.670
AUDIENCE: Yes, exactly.

00:40:14.670 --> 00:40:17.172
I see a lot of
people, in general,

00:40:17.172 --> 00:40:19.380
are very kind, sympathetic,
want to change the world.

00:40:19.380 --> 00:40:21.330
But when it comes to
personal relationship,

00:40:21.330 --> 00:40:25.560
because they are
very smart in brains,

00:40:25.560 --> 00:40:28.420
they don't tune in to
their empathic centers,

00:40:28.420 --> 00:40:30.960
or they do not have
developed empathetic center.

00:40:30.960 --> 00:40:32.659
They just relate to your brain.

00:40:32.659 --> 00:40:33.450
JUDITH ORLOFF: Yes.

00:40:33.450 --> 00:40:35.010
Yes, but they're kind people.

00:40:35.010 --> 00:40:36.260
AUDIENCE: They're kind people.

00:40:36.260 --> 00:40:37.680
They don't want to harm anybody.

00:40:37.680 --> 00:40:41.010
But they do not
understand their actions

00:40:41.010 --> 00:40:44.164
affect other human beings.

00:40:44.164 --> 00:40:46.080
JUDITH ORLOFF: Do you
find that that's common?

00:40:46.080 --> 00:40:46.820
AUDIENCE: That's common.

00:40:46.820 --> 00:40:47.570
JUDITH ORLOFF: Really?

00:40:47.570 --> 00:40:48.250
OK, well that--

00:40:48.250 --> 00:40:49.630
AUDIENCE: They are not
narcissists, necessarily.

00:40:49.630 --> 00:40:51.270
JUDITH ORLOFF: Right, right.

00:40:51.270 --> 00:40:54.090
That leaves an opening
on emotional training

00:40:54.090 --> 00:40:56.940
and intuitive training
for people here.

00:40:56.940 --> 00:40:58.620
It's something that's
really important

00:40:58.620 --> 00:41:01.350
to train in a safe environment.

00:41:01.350 --> 00:41:03.740
And if that's the
case, a lot of times

00:41:03.740 --> 00:41:05.200
it's something to think about.

00:41:05.200 --> 00:41:07.680
But in terms of your
expectations of them,

00:41:07.680 --> 00:41:09.309
you could come in
with a broken heart

00:41:09.309 --> 00:41:10.600
and they probably won't see it.

00:41:10.600 --> 00:41:11.590
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:41:11.590 --> 00:41:12.570
It happens.

00:41:12.570 --> 00:41:14.962
JUDITH ORLOFF: And to
not take that personally.

00:41:14.962 --> 00:41:16.170
AUDIENCE: Yeah, I understand.

00:41:16.170 --> 00:41:18.380
But is there a way--

00:41:18.380 --> 00:41:21.220
I was thinking
more in terms of--

00:41:21.220 --> 00:41:23.910
in Myers-Briggs test, you
go take an online test,

00:41:23.910 --> 00:41:26.490
and it tells you
what letters you are,

00:41:26.490 --> 00:41:29.830
ENTP, ISTP, whichever
might be the case.

00:41:29.830 --> 00:41:31.710
So it there an online
test I can go and say,

00:41:31.710 --> 00:41:32.970
hey, you're not empathic.

00:41:32.970 --> 00:41:37.360
Your empathy is out
of 1 to 100, 30 or 20.

00:41:37.360 --> 00:41:40.080
So that we know, and we
can say to each other,

00:41:40.080 --> 00:41:41.880
oh, we are 20, 100.

00:41:41.880 --> 00:41:45.882
So we know each other
in some objective way.

00:41:45.882 --> 00:41:47.340
JUDITH ORLOFF: In
an objective way.

00:41:47.340 --> 00:41:48.390
That would be in--

00:41:48.390 --> 00:41:50.370
and you would want to
pass that around and have

00:41:50.370 --> 00:41:51.260
everyone take it?

00:41:51.260 --> 00:41:51.960
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:41:51.960 --> 00:41:55.269
That would be the
Google way of doing it.

00:41:55.269 --> 00:41:56.310
JUDITH ORLOFF: All right.

00:41:56.310 --> 00:41:58.620
Well, there's certainly
a self-assessment test

00:41:58.620 --> 00:42:00.800
at the beginning of this
book with 20 questions

00:42:00.800 --> 00:42:03.450
that people can take,
and determine where

00:42:03.450 --> 00:42:06.240
they are on the empathy scale.

00:42:06.240 --> 00:42:08.850
But there could be other
ways to do it, too,

00:42:08.850 --> 00:42:13.080
in terms of creating more
formal tests and scores.

00:42:13.080 --> 00:42:15.510
But that's a good idea.

00:42:15.510 --> 00:42:17.250
But I think the goal
would be, really,

00:42:17.250 --> 00:42:19.680
to help people recognize.

00:42:19.680 --> 00:42:20.850
AUDIENCE: Recognize, right.

00:42:20.850 --> 00:42:22.725
JUDITH ORLOFF: Yeah,
because the more empathy

00:42:22.725 --> 00:42:24.870
you have, the better
your work environment

00:42:24.870 --> 00:42:27.040
is going to be because
you're going to feel safe.

00:42:27.040 --> 00:42:28.230
You don't want to ooze it.

00:42:28.230 --> 00:42:30.300
You don't overdo it.

00:42:30.300 --> 00:42:35.214
Sometimes empaths can help too
much and they give too much.

00:42:35.214 --> 00:42:36.630
They want to be
too compassionate.

00:42:36.630 --> 00:42:38.713
And they're looking at you
in the eyes too deeply,

00:42:38.713 --> 00:42:41.200
so it feels intrusive.

00:42:41.200 --> 00:42:42.030
That kind of thing.

00:42:42.030 --> 00:42:43.560
You don't want to become that.

00:42:43.560 --> 00:42:46.860
But you want to become
smart, intuitive, caring,

00:42:46.860 --> 00:42:47.940
and blend it all.

00:42:47.940 --> 00:42:50.352
And that takes some training,
sometimes, to do it.

00:42:50.352 --> 00:42:51.810
And hopefully, the
book will do it.

00:42:51.810 --> 00:42:53.002
But trainings can help.

00:42:53.002 --> 00:42:54.710
AUDIENCE: But first,
if you recognize it,

00:42:54.710 --> 00:42:57.570
at least you can know that this
person's at least like that.

00:42:57.570 --> 00:42:58.190
It's OK.

00:42:58.190 --> 00:42:59.207
We can be inclusive.

00:42:59.207 --> 00:43:00.290
JUDITH ORLOFF: Absolutely.

00:43:00.290 --> 00:43:03.110
But also, to recognize
that being a good person

00:43:03.110 --> 00:43:05.310
is the best thing
anyone could do.

00:43:05.310 --> 00:43:09.710
And even though they might
lack other abilities,

00:43:09.710 --> 00:43:14.290
if you're a good person, that's
a beautiful, beautiful thing.

00:43:14.290 --> 00:43:15.040
It really is.

00:43:15.040 --> 00:43:19.540
So to recognize that in each
other, and to affirm that--

00:43:19.540 --> 00:43:22.840
namaste, I respect
the spirit within you.

00:43:22.840 --> 00:43:24.580
To be able to say
that to each other,

00:43:24.580 --> 00:43:26.680
even with all your faults--

00:43:26.680 --> 00:43:28.480
We have tons of
faults, all of us.

00:43:28.480 --> 00:43:29.870
We're not perfect.

00:43:29.870 --> 00:43:34.420
But if we do the best we
can and we're loving people,

00:43:34.420 --> 00:43:36.910
give people credit
where credit is due.

00:43:36.910 --> 00:43:38.740
And when you can
affirm that in others,

00:43:38.740 --> 00:43:40.750
the whole environment
in the work environment

00:43:40.750 --> 00:43:44.410
can just increase the vibration,
increase the frequency,

00:43:44.410 --> 00:43:46.450
when you do that, as
opposed to looking at all

00:43:46.450 --> 00:43:48.170
the negatives in someone.

00:43:48.170 --> 00:43:51.310
It's much easier to look at the
negatives and criticize them

00:43:51.310 --> 00:43:52.630
and what they're doing wrong.

00:43:52.630 --> 00:43:54.760
But the shift in
consciousness in terms

00:43:54.760 --> 00:43:56.950
of awareness of
empathy is trying

00:43:56.950 --> 00:44:00.010
to see the best in
people, not their worst.

00:44:00.010 --> 00:44:02.800
You want to bring out
the best in people.

00:44:02.800 --> 00:44:04.870
AUDIENCE: When we
talk about empathy,

00:44:04.870 --> 00:44:08.020
normally we talk about
social with other people.

00:44:08.020 --> 00:44:12.220
So I have a separate
question, a little different.

00:44:12.220 --> 00:44:14.500
Here, I'm engineer.

00:44:14.500 --> 00:44:18.490
I think a lot of other
engineers, and even Judith,

00:44:18.490 --> 00:44:21.670
yourself, you said
you like to work,

00:44:21.670 --> 00:44:23.440
like writing, by yourself.

00:44:23.440 --> 00:44:27.400
Sometimes I feel the stress,
actually from the work,

00:44:27.400 --> 00:44:31.660
not with interacting
with other people.

00:44:31.660 --> 00:44:33.520
When you have
something difficult,

00:44:33.520 --> 00:44:37.040
something you don't
understand for a while,

00:44:37.040 --> 00:44:41.260
especially later of
the day, you tired,

00:44:41.260 --> 00:44:46.510
or your cognitive
capability tends to be down.

00:44:46.510 --> 00:44:49.770
And in my personal experience,
sometimes in that situation,

00:44:49.770 --> 00:44:52.570
I start to have self-doubt.

00:44:52.570 --> 00:44:56.250
And it's become a
downward spiral.

00:44:56.250 --> 00:45:02.230
And that negative energy
I can bring with me home,

00:45:02.230 --> 00:45:04.540
even though I'm
already out of work.

00:45:04.540 --> 00:45:06.310
I still think about it.

00:45:06.310 --> 00:45:11.350
But maybe after a night, the
next day, I look at it again.

00:45:11.350 --> 00:45:12.880
I can figure it out.

00:45:12.880 --> 00:45:14.740
It seems so simple.

00:45:14.740 --> 00:45:19.310
So what can you suggest
to do to prevent just

00:45:19.310 --> 00:45:23.770
to bring the negative
frustration out of work

00:45:23.770 --> 00:45:29.060
when you want to not think
about it at that time?

00:45:29.060 --> 00:45:30.560
JUDITH ORLOFF: A
very good question.

00:45:30.560 --> 00:45:34.300
How do you not take
the work energy home?

00:45:34.300 --> 00:45:36.317
And you mentioned self-doubt?

00:45:36.317 --> 00:45:36.900
AUDIENCE: Yes.

00:45:36.900 --> 00:45:37.990
JUDITH ORLOFF: Did you
mention self-doubt?

00:45:37.990 --> 00:45:40.540
AUDIENCE: Yeah, because
I can't figure this out.

00:45:40.540 --> 00:45:43.252
Maybe I was not good enough.

00:45:43.252 --> 00:45:44.710
JUDITH ORLOFF: All
right, well, I'm

00:45:44.710 --> 00:45:47.260
a big believer in affirmations.

00:45:47.260 --> 00:45:50.070
And so it's important
to really affirm,

00:45:50.070 --> 00:45:52.510
every day, what you did well.

00:45:52.510 --> 00:45:55.150
And at the end of the day, you
can make that a ritual, to just

00:45:55.150 --> 00:45:56.620
say, what did I do well today?

00:45:56.620 --> 00:45:57.650
What did I contribute?

00:45:57.650 --> 00:45:59.080
And it could be
the tiniest thing.

00:45:59.080 --> 00:46:00.130
It could be a big thing.

00:46:00.130 --> 00:46:01.240
It doesn't matter.

00:46:01.240 --> 00:46:04.210
But instead of--
the self-doubt, when

00:46:04.210 --> 00:46:07.300
I talk about the demon
and the Buddha inside,

00:46:07.300 --> 00:46:10.360
the self-doubt comes
from more the demon side,

00:46:10.360 --> 00:46:12.660
where you have to work with it.

00:46:12.660 --> 00:46:13.990
Everybody has self-doubt.

00:46:13.990 --> 00:46:15.910
We all have self-doubt.

00:46:15.910 --> 00:46:17.020
When you affirm--

00:46:17.020 --> 00:46:19.240
I did this well today.

00:46:19.240 --> 00:46:21.220
I did that well today.

00:46:21.220 --> 00:46:22.810
I was breathing today.

00:46:22.810 --> 00:46:23.830
I was walking today.

00:46:23.830 --> 00:46:24.680
I came to work.

00:46:24.680 --> 00:46:26.260
I had a day of life.

00:46:26.260 --> 00:46:30.880
Really, you could always get
back to that, to affirm that.

00:46:30.880 --> 00:46:33.250
And also to have a
closure meditation when

00:46:33.250 --> 00:46:35.470
you are ready to leave work--

00:46:35.470 --> 00:46:37.840
to actually sit,
close your eyes,

00:46:37.840 --> 00:46:41.050
breathe, center
yourself, say thank you

00:46:41.050 --> 00:46:42.830
for this opportunity
of work today.

00:46:42.830 --> 00:46:44.290
And now I'm leaving.

00:46:44.290 --> 00:46:49.630
And so to have an official
ritual of closure, and to let

00:46:49.630 --> 00:46:51.970
go of what happened at work.

00:46:51.970 --> 00:46:53.980
And that will help you.

00:46:53.980 --> 00:46:56.530
When I've finished
with my patients,

00:46:56.530 --> 00:46:58.930
usually I forget about it.

00:46:58.930 --> 00:47:01.150
I go on to the next
thing, unless there's

00:47:01.150 --> 00:47:04.090
something in particular
that I need to think

00:47:04.090 --> 00:47:05.560
about a little bit more.

00:47:05.560 --> 00:47:06.490
But I go on.

00:47:06.490 --> 00:47:08.810
I'm 100% present
when I'm working.

00:47:08.810 --> 00:47:11.140
Like with here,
I'm 100% present.

00:47:11.140 --> 00:47:14.670
But when I go on, I want
to grab the next moments

00:47:14.670 --> 00:47:16.600
and inhabit the next moment.

00:47:16.600 --> 00:47:18.730
So it's good, as a
sensitive person,

00:47:18.730 --> 00:47:22.524
to be present in the moment,
and then keep moving.

00:47:22.524 --> 00:47:23.440
It's like the warrior.

00:47:23.440 --> 00:47:26.490
You make your yell,
and then you move.

00:47:26.490 --> 00:47:27.550
And that's it.

00:47:27.550 --> 00:47:31.450
And so that's important to think
about, to be in the moment.

00:47:31.450 --> 00:47:33.490
And how do you be in the moment?

00:47:33.490 --> 00:47:34.750
You can have a mantra, even.

00:47:34.750 --> 00:47:36.290
Let it be.

00:47:36.290 --> 00:47:38.590
I'm being in the now.

00:47:38.590 --> 00:47:40.720
And to bring your
mind back-- because we

00:47:40.720 --> 00:47:44.230
have control over our thoughts,
our attitudes, and our mind.

00:47:44.230 --> 00:47:46.000
And so when we go
into self-doubt,

00:47:46.000 --> 00:47:47.320
you go, ah, self-doubt.

00:47:47.320 --> 00:47:48.640
I know you.

00:47:48.640 --> 00:47:52.450
Instead, I am going to breathe,
I'm going to focus on my heart,

00:47:52.450 --> 00:47:54.930
and I'm going to look
at what I did well.

00:47:54.930 --> 00:47:57.400
And let's say I need
improvement in something.

00:47:57.400 --> 00:47:59.710
I will work on that.

00:47:59.710 --> 00:48:02.540
We all are constantly
works in progress.

00:48:02.540 --> 00:48:04.670
And so to have a
lot of compassion

00:48:04.670 --> 00:48:07.490
for yourself every day,
and what you go through--

00:48:07.490 --> 00:48:09.890
we all go through so much.

00:48:09.890 --> 00:48:15.290
As a psychiatrist, I know well
how much we all go through.

00:48:15.290 --> 00:48:17.690
And so just give people a break.

00:48:17.690 --> 00:48:19.100
See the best in them.

00:48:19.100 --> 00:48:22.910
And try and be empathic
for what they go through,

00:48:22.910 --> 00:48:26.780
even if it's not something,
maybe, you can relate to.

00:48:26.780 --> 00:48:30.260
But if you're empathic
and your heart goes out,

00:48:30.260 --> 00:48:31.490
that's a good thing.

00:48:31.490 --> 00:48:33.140
It's really a beautiful
thing to relate

00:48:33.140 --> 00:48:35.272
to one another in that way.

00:48:35.272 --> 00:48:37.150
AUDIENCE: Hello.

00:48:37.150 --> 00:48:39.130
Along those same
lines, I find what's

00:48:39.130 --> 00:48:42.880
really emotional draining for
me is being constantly connected

00:48:42.880 --> 00:48:46.210
via my phone or social
media, things like that.

00:48:46.210 --> 00:48:48.460
Do you find that it's
important, especially

00:48:48.460 --> 00:48:51.610
for sensitive people, to have
that time to disconnect, maybe

00:48:51.610 --> 00:48:53.190
have a day without their phone?

00:48:53.190 --> 00:48:56.184
Is there tips and tools
that you'd recommend?

00:48:56.184 --> 00:48:58.600
JUDITH ORLOFF: I think it's
important to have a technology

00:48:58.600 --> 00:49:04.540
fast, and not go on social
media, and turn off your phone,

00:49:04.540 --> 00:49:08.230
and leave your phone at home,
and go for a walk on the beach

00:49:08.230 --> 00:49:11.440
so that you're not
tethered to the phone.

00:49:11.440 --> 00:49:13.690
Even in the gym,
sometimes I bring my phone

00:49:13.690 --> 00:49:18.400
and I put it on the treadmill,
and I have to talk to myself.

00:49:18.400 --> 00:49:20.210
Just leave it in the locker.

00:49:20.210 --> 00:49:21.340
Don't bring it.

00:49:21.340 --> 00:49:24.520
Your world can exist for
a short period of time

00:49:24.520 --> 00:49:25.870
without that phone.

00:49:25.870 --> 00:49:28.410
But it's very
addictive technology.

00:49:28.410 --> 00:49:32.770
So you have to really make that
extra effort to say no to it.

00:49:32.770 --> 00:49:34.720
And it makes me feel
so much better when

00:49:34.720 --> 00:49:36.510
I'm not near anything.

00:49:36.510 --> 00:49:41.035
There's a monastery that we
go to sometimes in retreat,

00:49:41.035 --> 00:49:42.880
Tassajara Monastery.

00:49:42.880 --> 00:49:44.290
They don't even
have electricity.

00:49:44.290 --> 00:49:46.990
They have no cell phone covers.

00:49:46.990 --> 00:49:48.130
They have no electricity.

00:49:48.130 --> 00:49:49.600
Kerosene lamps.

00:49:49.600 --> 00:49:53.520
So you're forced into
a beautiful retreat

00:49:53.520 --> 00:49:55.100
without technology.

00:49:55.100 --> 00:49:57.850
So I think that makes you
better when you come to work,

00:49:57.850 --> 00:49:59.490
when you have those breaks.

00:49:59.490 --> 00:50:02.320
Because if you keep checking,
and checking, and checking,

00:50:02.320 --> 00:50:05.170
it puts you in a
zombie-like state.

00:50:05.170 --> 00:50:07.120
And that's not in the body.

00:50:07.120 --> 00:50:09.940
And so to put it down a
little bit and go dance--

00:50:09.940 --> 00:50:13.840
I think dancing, what you
mentioned, or movement,

00:50:13.840 --> 00:50:17.080
any kind of movement,
the Qigong movement,

00:50:17.080 --> 00:50:20.800
dancing, walking,
exercising, looking up

00:50:20.800 --> 00:50:24.170
at the stars and the sun,
it's just replenishing.

00:50:24.170 --> 00:50:27.610
It's very important
without technology.

00:50:27.610 --> 00:50:29.800
SPEAKER 1: I just want
to add one thing on that,

00:50:29.800 --> 00:50:31.840
is when we talked
about the children

00:50:31.840 --> 00:50:35.650
and what we're teaching our
kids that are our future,

00:50:35.650 --> 00:50:39.040
is we're teaching them
this importance of how

00:50:39.040 --> 00:50:40.720
much our phones are.

00:50:40.720 --> 00:50:45.160
And they will say, what do
you mean you lost your phone?

00:50:45.160 --> 00:50:46.890
What are you going to do?

00:50:46.890 --> 00:50:50.620
Even they, as young as five, are
picking up on our attachments

00:50:50.620 --> 00:50:52.390
to our phones.

00:50:52.390 --> 00:50:54.130
SPEAKER 2: I had my
daughter very worried

00:50:54.130 --> 00:50:56.350
one night because my
husband went out for a walk

00:50:56.350 --> 00:50:58.210
and didn't have his phone.

00:50:58.210 --> 00:51:00.790
And I thought, oh, this is--

00:51:00.790 --> 00:51:03.720
A Day Without a Phone, I
think it's a new G to G class.

00:51:06.412 --> 00:51:08.620
JUDITH ORLOFF: And thank
you both, Heather and Wendy,

00:51:08.620 --> 00:51:10.030
for having me here.

00:51:10.030 --> 00:51:12.905
And thank you all for coming.

00:51:12.905 --> 00:51:13.780
SPEAKER 2: Thank you.

00:51:13.780 --> 00:51:15.900
SPEAKER 1: Thank
you all for coming.

